{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16110"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16110"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.2,0.4,0,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74153"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8801"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21010"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74153"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, primordial germ cells must reach their final destination to form the reproductive cells of the developing organism. These cells undergo a remarkable journey during weeks 4-5 of development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the origin and migration pathway of primordial germ cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arise from the primitive streak","Develop within the gonadal ridge","Originate in yolk sac wall and migrate to developing gonads","Form within the coelomic epithelium","Differentiate from intermediate mesoderm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that primordial germ cells \u003Cstrong\u003Eoriginate in yolk sac wall and migrate to developing gonads\u003C/strong\u003E. These cells first appear in the wall of the yolk sac near the allantois during week 4 of development. They then actively migrate along the dorsal mesentery of the hindgut to reach the developing gonads by week 5.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArise from the primitive streak\u003C/strong\u003E - While many embryonic tissues derive from the primitive streak, primordial germ cells have an extraembryonic origin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelop within the gonadal ridge\u003C/strong\u003E - They migrate to the gonadal ridge but do not originate there\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForm within the coelomic epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E - The coelomic epithelium contributes to gonadal supporting cells but not to germ cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDifferentiate from intermediate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E - They have an endodermal origin in the yolk sac wall, not a mesodermal origin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe migration of primordial germ cells is guided by chemical signals including stem cell factor. Once in the gonads, they will give rise to all future gametes through meiosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primordial germ cells originate in the yolk sac wall and migrate to the developing gonads during week 4-5 of embryonic development.","Primordial germ cells give rise to all gametes (sperm or eggs) in the adult organism.","Migration of primordial germ cells is guided by chemical signals including stem cell factor."],"references":["Nikolic A, Volarevic V, Armstrong L, Lako M, Stojkovic M. Primordial Germ Cells: Current Knowledge and Perspectives. Stem Cells Int. 2016;2016:1741072. doi: 10.1155/2016/1741072. Epub 2015 Nov 9. PMID: 26635880; PMCID: PMC4655300.","Park TS, Galic Z, Conway AE, Lindgren A, van Handel BJ, Magnusson M, Richter L, Teitell MA, Mikkola HK, Lowry WE, Plath K, Clark AT. Derivation of primordial germ cells from human embryonic and induced pluripotent stem cells is significantly improved by coculture with human fetal gonadal cells. Stem Cells. 2009 Apr;27(4):783-95. doi: 10.1002/stem.13. PMID: 19350678; PMCID: PMC4357362.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16110"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:51:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:52:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8801"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74153"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati